1
00:01:24,484 --> 00:01:26,195
Darling?

2
00:02:02,815 --> 00:02:05,401
Oh, darling.

3
00:02:31,176 --> 00:02:33,218
But sex.

4
00:02:33,218 --> 00:02:35,221
You are 23.

5
00:02:35,222 --> 00:02:38,390
Not an easy age
for abstinence, is it?

6
00:02:38,391 --> 00:02:40,644
Tolstoy does not approve
of sexual relations.

7
00:02:40,645 --> 00:02:43,230
I know this.
He despises them, in fact.

8
00:02:44,063 --> 00:02:46,524
Well, I don't mean
to belabor the point,

9
00:02:46,525 --> 00:02:50,110
but last summer
I arranged for a manservant

10
00:02:50,111 --> 00:02:53,156
who proceeded to ruin
two housemaids, just like that.

11
00:02:53,157 --> 00:02:54,366
He was very upset.

12
00:02:54,367 --> 00:02:57,242
This would not be a problem
with me. I'm a vegetarian.

13
00:02:57,243 --> 00:02:58,870
I am celibate.

14
00:02:58,871 --> 00:03:00,580
I'm also a vegetarian.

15
00:03:00,581 --> 00:03:04,709
My dear boy, if you were to become
Tolstoy's private secretary,

16
00:03:04,710 --> 00:03:06,503
you would be given a great gift.

17
00:03:06,504 --> 00:03:08,420
Vladimir Grigorevich,
please know

18
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:12,592
that I understand what a privilege this
position presents.

19
00:03:12,593 --> 00:03:17,264
But since becoming a Tolstoyan,
I have become so eager to learn,

20
00:03:17,265 --> 00:03:20,182
to discuss ideas,
to perfect my very soul.

21
00:03:20,182 --> 00:03:22,769
Yes. Well...

22
00:03:22,770 --> 00:03:27,188
We have a lot to do if we are to get his
work to the people.

23
00:03:27,189 --> 00:03:29,568
We?
Yes, we.

24
00:03:31,111 --> 00:03:34,281
If we can encourage the spread
of passive resistance,

25
00:03:34,282 --> 00:03:36,866
just think of it, Valentin.

26
00:03:36,867 --> 00:03:40,412
Thousands of ordinary
Russians

27
00:03:40,496 --> 00:03:43,789
casting off centuries of political
and spiritual oppression.

28
00:03:43,789 --> 00:03:48,086
In the name of truth and freedom.
Truth and freedom. Yes, yes.

29
00:03:48,087 --> 00:03:52,007
But, still, there are
many, many enemies.

30
00:03:52,008 --> 00:03:54,634
Enemies?
Come.

31
00:03:54,635 --> 00:03:56,926
The czar's police.

32
00:03:56,927 --> 00:03:59,139
Now, you will be followed
when you leave here,

33
00:03:59,140 --> 00:04:02,974
and the Church will stop at nothing
to bring him back into the fold.

34
00:04:02,975 --> 00:04:06,271
And then, of course,
there is the countess.

35
00:04:06,980 --> 00:04:09,649
Her dogged attachment
to private property,

36
00:04:09,650 --> 00:04:12,444
her public criticism
of our movement.

37
00:04:13,819 --> 00:04:15,528
But the point is

38
00:04:15,530 --> 00:04:18,489
he needs a man of your
intellectual gifts around him.

39
00:04:18,490 --> 00:04:20,743
Someone who understands
his goals.

40
00:04:20,745 --> 00:04:23,078
And they still won't
let me see him.

41
00:04:23,079 --> 00:04:25,790
They keep me under
house arrest.

42
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:31,295
I have another task for you,
my dear.

43
00:04:31,338 --> 00:04:35,925
I want you to keep
a diary for me.

44
00:04:36,593 --> 00:04:39,846
I need to know what goes on
at Yasnaya Polyana.

45
00:04:39,846 --> 00:04:41,054
Mm-hm.

46
00:04:41,055 --> 00:04:43,181
You let me know
who visits the house,

47
00:04:43,182 --> 00:04:47,019
any talk of the copyright to his work,
any contact with the Church,

48
00:04:47,019 --> 00:04:49,395
anything the countess says.

49
00:04:49,396 --> 00:04:52,567
Anything?
She's very, very dangerous.

50
00:04:56,322 --> 00:04:59,197
Whoa, whoa.

51
00:04:59,740 --> 00:05:01,241
Godspeed, my boy.

52
00:05:01,242 --> 00:05:03,786
And remember what I said.
Mm-hm.

53
00:05:03,786 --> 00:05:07,206
Write everything down.

54
00:05:08,040 --> 00:05:09,334
Driver!

55
00:05:09,334 --> 00:05:11,877
Walk on. Whoa, whoa.

56
00:05:34,901 --> 00:05:36,485
Good morning, countess.

57
00:05:36,778 --> 00:05:38,697
Are you rolling? Are you rolling?
I am.

58
00:05:38,697 --> 00:05:41,949
Countess? Countess?

59
00:05:46,829 --> 00:05:48,037
It doesn't matter.

60
00:05:48,038 --> 00:05:50,748
If my heart stopped beating,
I'd still go riding today.

61
00:05:50,750 --> 00:05:52,376
Your pulse is
my responsibility.

62
00:05:52,377 --> 00:05:54,419
No. It's mine.
Fine.

63
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:56,588
If you must ride,
I insist you wear a coat.

64
00:05:56,589 --> 00:05:58,507
Even the sun is cold today.
Oh, this!

65
00:05:58,507 --> 00:06:02,596
This is impossible!
These people are parasites!

66
00:06:03,096 --> 00:06:06,056
"The Countess Tolstoy
is estranged from her husband.

67
00:06:06,057 --> 00:06:08,600
They barely speak."

68
00:06:08,601 --> 00:06:10,811
And they gossip
about us in Paris.

69
00:06:10,812 --> 00:06:13,688
"They do not share a similar view of
religion or politics."

70
00:06:13,689 --> 00:06:15,149
You think that's inaccurate?

71
00:06:15,149 --> 00:06:17,275
I think it's none of the world's
bloody business.

72
00:06:17,276 --> 00:06:20,028
What are you doing? Why do you write down
everything we say?

73
00:06:20,029 --> 00:06:21,237
Don't do that.

74
00:06:21,238 --> 00:06:24,533
Dushan Petrovich,
you are scribbling again.

75
00:06:26,036 --> 00:06:28,746
Oh, Leovochka, why do you insist on
dressing like that?

76
00:06:28,747 --> 00:06:32,040
What do you mean, like what?
Like the man who looks after sheep.

77
00:06:32,041 --> 00:06:34,209
It wasn't meant to offend you.

78
00:06:34,209 --> 00:06:37,463
You're a count, for God's sake.

79
00:06:37,463 --> 00:06:38,963
Darling,
where are you going?

80
00:06:38,964 --> 00:06:41,633
Riding with Sasha.
Don't expect us for lunch.

81
00:06:41,634 --> 00:06:43,885
Lev Nikolayevich,
you've forgotten your coat.

82
00:06:43,887 --> 00:06:45,221
Dushan, are you fretting?

83
00:06:45,221 --> 00:06:48,516
Yes, because you refuse
to look after yourself.

84
00:07:33,394 --> 00:07:36,313
Telyatinki was created
by Vladimir Grigorevich

85
00:07:36,314 --> 00:07:38,608
as a center for the movement.

86
00:07:38,608 --> 00:07:43,528
We're all equals here, you know,
as Tolstoy teaches us.

87
00:07:43,529 --> 00:07:45,822
This is a place of freedom.

88
00:07:50,452 --> 00:07:52,328
It's a beautiful day.

89
00:07:52,329 --> 00:07:55,209
Yes, but we'll pay for it.

90
00:07:56,084 --> 00:07:57,417
Toolshed is there.

91
00:07:57,418 --> 00:08:00,878
That's the meeting room,
and this is the dormitory.

92
00:08:00,879 --> 00:08:02,673
I found it!

93
00:08:02,923 --> 00:08:05,049
Afternoon.
Yes, hello.

94
00:08:05,050 --> 00:08:07,846
You are expected at Yasnaya Polyana
in the morning,

95
00:08:07,846 --> 00:08:09,346
first thing.
First thing?

96
00:08:09,346 --> 00:08:12,181
You'll need to be on the road early.
It's nearly two hours away.

97
00:08:12,182 --> 00:08:16,061
I look forward to it.
Yes. You're lucky.

98
00:08:16,062 --> 00:08:17,939
We're all envious.

99
00:08:26,072 --> 00:08:28,365
I'll see you in the morning.

100
00:08:28,365 --> 00:08:30,617
If we're spared.

101
00:08:37,918 --> 00:08:39,375
Right.

102
00:08:39,376 --> 00:08:42,548
And out.

103
00:08:44,048 --> 00:08:46,009
In.

104
00:08:48,095 --> 00:08:51,847
Emma, can you come?
We need you in the house.

105
00:08:57,480 --> 00:08:59,187
Come in.

106
00:09:04,110 --> 00:09:07,947
Brought you a glass of tea.
That's very kind of you.

107
00:09:10,951 --> 00:09:13,451
It's your first day.

108
00:09:13,452 --> 00:09:15,581
Enjoy it.

109
00:09:20,711 --> 00:09:22,961
You met Sergeyenko?

110
00:09:23,504 --> 00:09:25,756
Last night, yes.

111
00:09:26,799 --> 00:09:28,466
What do you think?

112
00:09:28,467 --> 00:09:30,927
I thought he seemed
very sincere.

113
00:09:30,928 --> 00:09:32,429
Thank you.

114
00:09:33,597 --> 00:09:35,139
What?

115
00:09:35,140 --> 00:09:38,226
Is that what you think?
I think that...

116
00:09:39,645 --> 00:09:43,231
I think I've just arrived.
What was your name?

117
00:09:43,232 --> 00:09:46,653
Masha. But you should
still say what you think.

118
00:09:46,653 --> 00:09:49,072
I mean, not just about him.

119
00:09:49,072 --> 00:09:50,697
Like we all should.

120
00:09:51,991 --> 00:09:53,576
Yes.

121
00:09:58,831 --> 00:10:00,667
Excuse me.

122
00:10:03,836 --> 00:10:06,004
Thank you for the tea.

123
00:10:11,885 --> 00:10:14,971
He's a sorry, old, tight-assed
stick-in-the-mud,

124
00:10:14,972 --> 00:10:18,519
but, yes, he's sincere.

125
00:11:05,899 --> 00:11:07,942
Hello?

126
00:11:10,278 --> 00:11:12,197
Out of the way.

127
00:11:14,448 --> 00:11:16,576
Hello?

128
00:11:17,409 --> 00:11:20,120
Ah. Excuse me.

129
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:21,497
You.

130
00:11:21,499 --> 00:11:23,667
You're the new secretary?
Yes.

131
00:11:23,668 --> 00:11:25,625
Valentin Fedorovich Bulgakov.

132
00:11:25,626 --> 00:11:29,715
Papa is out. You can wait
upstairs in the library.

133
00:12:09,672 --> 00:12:13,381
I am so glad you're here.

134
00:12:16,596 --> 00:12:18,971
I'm so glad.

135
00:12:21,475 --> 00:12:25,312
God bless you.
Pardon me. I'm mortified.

136
00:12:25,312 --> 00:12:27,730
I sneeze sometimes
when I get nervous.

137
00:12:29,774 --> 00:12:31,942
Yes.

138
00:12:31,942 --> 00:12:35,487
Now, Vladimir Grigorevich has already
written about you at lengths.

139
00:12:35,489 --> 00:12:39,576
I don't need that.
What I do need is your help.

140
00:12:39,576 --> 00:12:42,370
My manifesto against
the government is hard work.

141
00:12:42,370 --> 00:12:47,167
They commit their idiotic abuses
faster than I can catalog them.

142
00:12:47,168 --> 00:12:48,459
Yes.

143
00:12:48,461 --> 00:12:50,961
And then there's the new book,
the compendium.

144
00:12:50,961 --> 00:12:52,797
Vladimir Grigorevich
told me all about it.

145
00:12:52,798 --> 00:12:56,759
He says that you say that all the world's
religions share common truths.

146
00:12:56,759 --> 00:12:58,552
It's very exciting.
No, one truth.

147
00:12:58,552 --> 00:13:02,889
One single organizing principle.
And can you guess what that is?

148
00:13:02,975 --> 00:13:05,100
Um...
Eh?

149
00:13:05,100 --> 00:13:08,895
Love. Love. Simple.

150
00:13:09,563 --> 00:13:12,149
Yeah, but I want
to talk about you.

151
00:13:12,485 --> 00:13:14,985
How are you?
And how was your journey?

152
00:13:14,985 --> 00:13:16,989
Come, sit down.

153
00:13:16,989 --> 00:13:21,492
I was born on that sofa.
No, no, sit, sit.

154
00:13:21,494 --> 00:13:24,827
Myself, my brother, my children,

155
00:13:24,828 --> 00:13:27,538
five or six of them, at least.
Right here.

156
00:13:27,539 --> 00:13:29,332
Congratulations.

157
00:13:31,504 --> 00:13:35,215
Well, I've read your essays.

158
00:13:35,716 --> 00:13:38,552
How's the work progressing?

159
00:13:44,182 --> 00:13:46,769
My boy, what is it?

160
00:13:47,519 --> 00:13:50,144
Oh, I've upset you in some way.
No.

161
00:13:50,145 --> 00:13:52,981
Was it the sofa?
I mean, it's only a sofa.

162
00:13:52,982 --> 00:13:55,400
The sofa's wonderful.

163
00:13:55,943 --> 00:13:57,194
I...

164
00:13:57,196 --> 00:13:59,572
I'm very happy.
Mm-hm.

165
00:13:59,572 --> 00:14:02,616
You're very kind to me.

166
00:14:03,951 --> 00:14:06,413
You see, I am no one,

167
00:14:06,413 --> 00:14:09,706
and you are Lev Tolstoy.

168
00:14:09,707 --> 00:14:13,086
And you ask me
about my work.

169
00:14:13,086 --> 00:14:16,088
I'll fetch you a glass of tea.

170
00:14:16,090 --> 00:14:18,298
Yes.
Now, you rest.

171
00:14:19,341 --> 00:14:24,053
Yeah, because there's work
for both of us to do, together!

172
00:14:24,054 --> 00:14:25,598
Yes.

173
00:14:25,600 --> 00:14:27,643
Yes.

174
00:14:28,100 --> 00:14:30,102
God.

175
00:14:31,270 --> 00:14:34,606
This machine, it really is
the most extraordinary thing.

176
00:14:34,607 --> 00:14:36,483
Mama, these people have nothing.

177
00:14:36,485 --> 00:14:39,571
No, it's not for lack of land
that the muzhiks live in poverty.

178
00:14:39,572 --> 00:14:42,322
It's because they have no willpower and
they drink too much.

179
00:14:42,323 --> 00:14:45,783
I am not suggesting
they be given land.

180
00:14:45,784 --> 00:14:47,952
Private property is the root
of the problem.

181
00:14:47,953 --> 00:14:50,999
We should be giving ours away.
God. Giving it to whom?

182
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:53,250
Yes, exactly.
I mean, this is ridiculous.

183
00:14:53,250 --> 00:14:56,504
You think because the peasants are poor,
they're somehow morally superior.

184
00:14:56,504 --> 00:14:58,755
I believe that wealth
corrupts us all.

185
00:14:58,756 --> 00:15:00,007
Yes, I do.

186
00:15:00,009 --> 00:15:02,216
Mm. It's a keystone
of the movement.

187
00:15:02,217 --> 00:15:04,678
Oh, God, I know
all about the movement.

188
00:15:05,429 --> 00:15:07,139
If the peasants
had money,

189
00:15:07,139 --> 00:15:09,643
they wouldn't surround
themselves, as we do,

190
00:15:09,644 --> 00:15:11,937
with footmen costing
10 rubles a month.

191
00:15:11,937 --> 00:15:15,566
No, they'd spend it
on drink and whores.

192
00:15:15,774 --> 00:15:18,192
Valentin Fedorovich.
Mm.

193
00:15:18,192 --> 00:15:19,735
What do you think?
Tea.

194
00:15:19,735 --> 00:15:23,781
You think that 50 years from now, people
will eat while grown men walk around

195
00:15:23,783 --> 00:15:26,033
waiting on them
hand and foot?

196
00:15:26,033 --> 00:15:27,745
I th... I think...
That's good.

197
00:15:29,328 --> 00:15:31,788
Bless you.
Stop scribbling.

198
00:15:31,789 --> 00:15:34,668
I mean, you all think
he's Christ, don't you?

199
00:15:34,668 --> 00:15:38,629
He thinks he's Christ.
I'm not...

200
00:15:38,673 --> 00:15:41,673
I don't believe Lev Nikolayevich
is Christ.

201
00:15:41,674 --> 00:15:43,550
Christ is Christ,
but, uh...

202
00:15:43,552 --> 00:15:44,970
But what?

203
00:15:44,971 --> 00:15:47,346
I do believe
he's one of the prophets.

204
00:15:47,346 --> 00:15:48,846
God speaks through him.

205
00:15:48,847 --> 00:15:50,807
I recognize the cadence
in his voice.

206
00:15:50,808 --> 00:15:52,850
Oh, God, this is unbearable.

207
00:15:52,851 --> 00:15:56,146
No wonder I feel lonely.
I'm surrounded by morons.

208
00:15:56,148 --> 00:15:59,024
Ma, you're being ridiculous.
Oh, am I?

209
00:15:59,024 --> 00:16:03,153
I have to sit here and listen to this talk
of love and God and equality,

210
00:16:03,153 --> 00:16:05,697
knowing all the time,
full well,

211
00:16:05,698 --> 00:16:08,867
that Count Generosity
here is about to give away
everything we own.

212
00:16:08,869 --> 00:16:12,163
Now, why do you keep
going on about this?

213
00:16:12,163 --> 00:16:15,874
Why do you think that we should profit from
the work I'm doing now?

214
00:16:15,875 --> 00:16:18,504
Which is only meant
for the sake of the people.

215
00:16:19,044 --> 00:16:21,172
Stop writing!

216
00:16:21,173 --> 00:16:25,717
Stop writing now!

217
00:16:37,688 --> 00:16:41,067
In defense of my gift,
please let me demonstrate.

218
00:16:41,067 --> 00:16:43,568
It's quite remarkable, really.

219
00:16:48,866 --> 00:16:52,661
<i>In the same way now,
a society of hunger,</i>

220
00:16:52,663 --> 00:16:55,831
<i>full of segregation...</i>

221
00:16:56,750 --> 00:16:57,957
<i>I understand,</i>

222
00:16:57,958 --> 00:17:01,922
<i>not only with my mind, or heart,
It's... It's your voice.</i>

223
00:17:01,923 --> 00:17:04,841
<i>but with my soul,
that the existence</i>

224
00:17:04,842 --> 00:17:07,009
<i>of tens of thousands...
It's your voice.</i>

225
00:17:07,011 --> 00:17:09,345
It's wonderful.
It's wonderful!

226
00:17:09,639 --> 00:17:11,765
It's tiresome.

227
00:17:12,057 --> 00:17:14,559
Another remarkable invention
will supersede it.

228
00:17:14,560 --> 00:17:17,062
Please excuse me.

229
00:17:17,772 --> 00:17:21,107
<i>No matter what all the learned men
in the world say...</i>

230
00:17:21,108 --> 00:17:23,985
Lev Nikolayevich is
something of a Luddite, I fear.

231
00:17:23,986 --> 00:17:26,028
<i>It is a crime.</i>

232
00:17:26,030 --> 00:17:30,449
<i>And one committed not once,
but constantly.</i>

233
00:17:30,450 --> 00:17:33,829
<i>I knew that I, with my luxury...</i>

234
00:17:59,104 --> 00:18:00,688
That's better.

235
00:18:04,317 --> 00:18:06,445
That's nice.

236
00:18:15,329 --> 00:18:17,872
That's very nice indeed.

237
00:18:51,407 --> 00:18:54,533
Do your parents often speak
to each other so bluntly?

238
00:18:54,534 --> 00:18:57,786
Mama doesn't understand
my father's goals,

239
00:18:57,787 --> 00:19:00,998
not since his work as a novelist
became secondary.

240
00:19:00,999 --> 00:19:05,711
His commitment to the
spiritual life offends her.

241
00:19:05,713 --> 00:19:08,631
They've fought
about it for years.

242
00:19:08,632 --> 00:19:11,843
Well, I'm sure
she means well by it.

243
00:19:14,513 --> 00:19:19,016
I see a fine young man
before me. Clear eyes,
nice features,

244
00:19:19,017 --> 00:19:21,393
rather handsome
in a peculiar sort of a way.

245
00:19:21,394 --> 00:19:22,937
Th... Thank you,
countess.

246
00:19:22,938 --> 00:19:25,148
Oh, please, call me
Sofya Andreyevna.

247
00:19:25,149 --> 00:19:29,360
We don't stand on formality here,
as you may have noticed.

248
00:19:29,361 --> 00:19:31,321
No, no. So many
young men nowadays

249
00:19:31,322 --> 00:19:35,867
spoil their good looks
with loose living, but you...

250
00:19:35,868 --> 00:19:40,455
Ooh, you're a real
